article.description: Lamar Odom never has been to the playoffs,  but if he continues to make big shots for the Heat, it may just be a matter of time.
article.headline: Miami snaps four-game skid
article.linkText: Heat hold on in fourth quarter to top Bucks
article.story: MIAMI (AP) -- This time, the Miami Heat didn't collapse in the fourth quarter. Rafer Alston tied his season high with 23 points and Caron Butler added 21 to help the Miami Heat hold off the Milwaukee Bucks 104-98 Thursday night and snap a four-game losing streak. Miami wasted a 16-point first-half lead, letting the Bucks rally to tie it 98-all with 1:09 left in the game. Lamar Odom broke the tie with a free throw for the Heat, and his runner from the left side gave Miami a three-point lead with 24 seconds left. "This was a good education because we're going to have a lot of games like this," Odom said. "We will take this experience, watch the film to see what we did well and apply it to the next game." On Tuesday, the Heat blew a 15-point lead and scored a season-low eight points in the fourth quarter in a loss to Toronto. Rasual Butler scored a season-high 20 points off the bench for Miami, which pulled into a tie with idle Boston for the eighth playoff spot in the Eastern Conference. Odom finished with 16 points, seven rebounds and nine assists. Alston, getting extended playing time with rookie Dwyane Wade out with an injury, made eight of nine shots, including 3-of-4 for 3-pointers. He also had eight assists against just one turnover and five rebounds. "The good thing was that I wasn't just standing around the 3-point line waiting for someone to kick it out," Alston said. "I didn't want to pass up opportunities to get to the basket." Alston's performance impressed his coach Stan Van Gundy. "His game will rate out about as good as you can have," Van Gundy said. "He was incredible. He played a phenomenal game for 43 minutes." Keith Van Horn scored 22 points and Michael Redd added 21 for Milwaukee, which had its four-game winning streak snapped. The Bucks beat Miami 108-104 last week. Milwaukee won the first of back-to-back games, beating Orlando 105-97 on Wednesday. But the Bucks started sluggishly Thursday, falling behind 9-0 in the first two minutes. "We started off completely flat, and we haven't done that in a long time," Desmond Mason said. "The Heat took advantage of it. We had opportunities to take the game over. When it got down to the stretch, they made a few more plays than we did." The Heat raced out to leads of 39-23 at the end of the first quarter and 60-49 at halftime. Milwaukee chipped away to start the third quarter, closing to 62-58 in the first three minutes. The Heat built their lead back to 10 points, but the Bucks cut it to 82-78 at the end of the period. Redd and Damon Jones sparked the Bucks with 10 points each in the third. Van Horn hit a 3-pointer to cut Miami's lead to 84-81 early in the fourth quarter, but Alston hit a pair of free throws, Eddie Jones scored on a reverse layup and Butler hit a jumper from the corner to give the Heat a 90-81 advantage. The Bucks answered with a 10-3 run, capped by a pair of free throws by Redd, to pull within 93-91 with 4:20 left. Toni Kukoc made a free throw to it 98-all with 1:09 left. Odom made one of two free throws to put Miami ahead 99-98. After Kukoc missed a 3-point try from the left wing, Odom followed by hitting a runner from the left baseline to make it 101-98 with 24 seconds to go. Van Horn missed on a drive, and Alston came up with the loose ball and was fouled. He knocked down both free throws to provide a 103-98 lead with 11 seconds left. "We did a great job of getting back in the game and giving ourselves a chance to win," Bucks coach Terry Porter said. "When you get back into a game like this, you have to have everything go right at the end. You can't miss a free throw and an open 3. We did, and they did a good job of executing their game plan on the offensive end." ^Notes:@ Before the game, the Heat activated guard Bimbo Coles and placed center Loren Woods on the injured list with a lower back strain. ... Backup forward Udonis Haslem of the Heat was cut above his left eye in the first half and needed seven stitches. ... Wade missed his second straight game for Miami with a bone contusion in his right foot and isn't expected back until March 9 against Orlando at the earliest. ... The early 9-0 lead was the best start by the Heat this season. Their 16-point lead at the end of the first period was their largest margin in a quarter... Bucks guard Damon Jones, whose 17 assists on Wednesday tied the NBA season high, had three against the Heat. ... Alston has made a 3-pointer in 28 straight games. ... The Bucks' three-game road winning streak came to an end.
